[1
Date: Wed 30 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Communicable Disease Report Weekly, Thu 24 May 2001 [edited
<http://www.phls.co.uk/publications/CDR%20Weekly/pages/news.html#hepc>

Hepatitis C lookback in 2 trusts in southern England
----------------------------------------------------
This week 2 Trusts have written to 228 patients informing them that they
may be at risk of hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection. The patients had all
had an exposure prone procedure performed by a health care worker who is
infected with HCV. The infected health care worker was diagnosed during the
investigation of acute hepatitis C in a patient who had undergone an
exposure prone procedure. The hospitals have set up a telephone helpline.
Since 1994, 4 other patient notification exercises in the United Kingdom
(UK) have followed investigations of hospital acquired HCV infections in
patients in which hepatitis C infected health care workers have been
revealed (1-5). These exercises have documented a total of 13 transmissions
of HCV to patients during exposure prone procedures.
In 3 studies the prevalence of antibody to HCV among health care workers in
the UK has been shown to be less than 0.3% (6-8). Current guidance in the
UK is that HCV infected health care workers associated with transmission
should not perform exposure prone procedures (1). Following advice from the
Advisory Group on Hepatitis, the Department of Health has recently issued a
consultation document to the health professions on HCV infected health care
workers. The consultation document covers issues such as testing of health
care workers and restrictions on working practices. Clinical guidelines on
the management of hepatitis C were published recently by the Royal College
of Physicians of London and the British Society of Gastroenterology (9).
References:
1. CDSC. Hepatitis C virus transmission from health care worker to patient.
Commun Dis Rep CDR Wkly 1995; 5: 121.
2. Duckworth GJ, Heptonstall J, Aitken C for the Incident Management Team
and Others. Transmission of hepatitis C virus from a surgeon to a patient.
Commun Dis Public Health 1999; 2: 188-92.
3. CDSC. Transmission of hepatitis C virus from surgeon to patient prompts
lookback. Commun Dis Rep CDR Wkly 1999; 9: 387.
