Source: The Harlow Star, Tue 29 May 2001 [edited
<http://www.herts-essex-news.co.uk/henpages/starpages/index.html>

Consequences of nosocomial transmission of HCV in Surrey hospital
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Hospital chiefs in Harlow (Essex) are offering blood tests to more than 70
patients after a former member of staff was found to have contracted
hepatitis C. An investigation began in the autumn after the virus was
transmitted to a patient at Epsom General Hospital in Surrey. The infection
was traced to an individual who went on to work in the Women's Health
Department at Princess Alexandra Hospital (PAH) [in Harlow, Essex and has
since left. A search through 850 patient records at PAH covering the period
from autumn 2000 to early this year [showed that 67 mothers and 7 babies
may have been placed at risk. Those affected have now been informed by
letter and offered blood tests.
Mike Roddis, PAH's medical director, said yesterday: "We have computerised
records of people treated in the department and have been able to identify
everyone with any involvement. The risk of hepatitis C infection from an
infected health care worker to a patient during a surgical procedure is
very small," said Dr Roddis. "Any patients found to be hepatitis C positive
will be seen and offered treatment." Most people who become infected suffer
no ill effects [in the acute phase, but the virus may cause chronic liver
disease.
